		<title>Ferocious Bass Lick + Developing Your Vocabulary (L#176)</title>
		<link>http://www.scottsbasslessons.com/licks/ferocious-major-scale-bass-lick.html</link>
		<comments>http://www.scottsbasslessons.com/licks/ferocious-major-scale-bass-lick.html#comments</comments>
		<pubDate>Thu, 17 Sep 2015 08:35:59 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[Travis Moore]]></dc:creator>
				<category><![CDATA[Licks]]></category>

		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://www.scottsbasslessons.com/?p=11761</guid>
		<description><![CDATA[<p>=== Lesson Overview In this lesson Scott takes you through a Ferocious Major Lick to really demonstrate how important and versatile the major scale is, especially when you get inventive with the intervals you use. The secondary focus of this...</p>
<p>The post <a rel="nofollow" href="http://www.scottsbasslessons.com/licks/ferocious-major-scale-bass-lick.html">Ferocious Bass Lick + Developing Your Vocabulary (L#176)</a> appeared first on <a rel="nofollow" href="http://www.scottsbasslessons.com">Online Bass Lessons</a>.</p>
]]></description>
				<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p><div><a href="http://www.scottsbasslessons.com/bass-academy" class="post_cta">Full tab/notation & workbook available to Academy members &raquo;</a></div><div class="video_wrap "><iframe src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/37iInttErqw" width="560" height="315" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen="allowfullscreen"></iframe></div></p>
</p>
<p><em>Want to try out the SBL Academy?! <a href="http://www.scottsbasslessons.com/bass-academy" target="_blank">Grab your 14 day free trial by clicking here.</a></em></p>
<p>
<p>===</p>
<h1>Lesson Overview</h1>
<p>In this lesson Scott takes you through a Ferocious <a href="http://www.scottsbasslessons.com/licks/jazz-lick-major-7th-type-chords-2.html" target="_blank">Major Lick</a> to really demonstrate how important and versatile the major scale is, especially when you get inventive with the intervals you use. The secondary focus of this lesson is on <a href="http://www.scottsbasslessons.com/improvisation/developing-your-vocabulary-with-the-blues-scale.html" target="_blank">developing vocabulary</a> and this is definitely a great lick to get into your vocabulary!</p>
<p>Don’t worry if the lick Scott plays in this lesson is a bit beyond your ability right now, there's still a lot you can take away from this lesson. Scott shows you how to play the fundamental <a href="http://www.scottsbasslessons.com/bass-lines-grooves/bass-grooves-articulation.html" target="_blank">groove</a> which you can learn on its own. As well as this Scott demonstrates how he would approach breaking the lick down into small phrases so that you can really focus in on them and iron out any technique issues that may arise. From there you can take those bite sized chunks and slowly build up to playing the whole lick at <a href="http://www.scottsbasslessons.com/technique/speed-bursts-bass-arpeggios-lesson.html">speed</a>. Then once you have the lick together you can add it into your own vocabulary and start using it in context.</p>
<p>If the lick is just outside your ability you may well surprise yourself by giving it a try! Using this approach of breaking lines down is a really great way to push yourself to try harder parts, that may usually be beyond your skill level, and really improve your playing.</p>
<p>The lick itself is constructed from almost entirely diatonic notes. A diatonic note is a note from within the scale. So in this instance the scale is C Major so the diatonic notes would be - C D E F G A B. The only acception to this is an Eb played at the begging of the lick which resolves (through a slide) to the major 3rd (E).</p>
<p>Scott also discusses how fundamental the major scale is to all other major harmony. In effect all the modes, <a href="http://www.scottsbasslessons.com/improvisation/gary-willis-style-pentatonic-lick.html" target="_blank">pentatonics</a> and <a href="http://www.scottsbasslessons.com/technique/speed-bursts-bass-arpeggios-lesson.html" target="_blank">arpeggios</a> are built on the same notes that are used in the Major Scale. The only differences are the sequence in which the notes are played and, in the case of pentonics, that some notes are skipped.</p>
<p>If you want to learn more about the modes, check out Scott's "Discover the modes" mini course in the <a href="http://www.scottsbasslessons.com/scotts-backstage-bonuses" target="_blank">SBL toolkit</a>.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<h1>Your Homework</h1>
<p>Have you tried breaking the bass lines and licks you're trying to learn into smaller bite size phrases rather than attacking the whole thing at once?</p>
<p>Do you regularly learn new bass lines and licks that are slightly out of your comfort zone to help push your bass playing to the next level?</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>- See you all next week, Travis Moore - Academy Community Manager.</p>
