		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://www.scottsbasslessons.com/?p=11267</guid>
		<description><![CDATA[<p>If you’re anything like me, every now and again you just want to learn a good ol’ dirty sounding groove that makes you wanna say… “Ooof”… Well if today is one of those day’s for you, you’re in the right...</p>
<p>The post <a rel="nofollow" href="http://www.scottsbasslessons.com/improvisation/bass-groove-lesson-vocabulary.html">Filthy Bass Groove Deconstruction + Expanding Your Vocabulary (L#170)</a> appeared first on <a rel="nofollow" href="http://www.scottsbasslessons.com">Online Bass Lessons</a>.</p>
]]></description>
				<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>If you’re anything like me, every now and again you just want to learn a good ol’ dirty sounding <a href="http://www.scottsbasslessons.com/riff-of-the-week/funk-soul-groove-bass-playing.html" target="_blank">groove</a> that makes you wanna say… <em>“Ooof”</em>…</p>
<p>Well if today is one of those day’s for you, you’re in the right place!</p>
<p>As well as teaching you a <a href="http://www.scottsbasslessons.com/bass-lines-grooves/danny-mo-morris-r-b-bass-lesson.html" target="_blank">great bass line</a> that will make anyone in their right mind <em>get their groove on</em>, I’m also going to demonstrate a couple of great harmonic devices that you can use over static dominant chords immediately.</p>
<p>I wanna give you the <em>“Ooof factor”!</em></p>
<p>This groove is based around an E dominant 7th style vamp, and both of the licks include the minor 3rd. Now if you know anything about dominant <a href="http://www.scottsbasslessons.com/chords/playing-chords-on-bass-getting-your-voice-leading-together.html" target="_blank">chords</a> you’ll know that they are an extension of the major triad, i.e. the minor 3rd is essentially a wrong note - but, in this style of groove it still works! In fact it does more than work, it sounds fantastic and gives the bass line that real bluesy style sound.</p>
<p>I incorporate these types of lines and runs within my grooves as they’re a great way of expanding of the dominant 7th sound, and in-turn give you more options when grooving and soloing over static dominant chords.</p>
<p>As always, see you in the shed…</p>
<p>Scott :)</p>
</p>
